        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> `nvim --clean` disables shada\n\nYes, true. So I tried:\n```lua\n  \" :help restore-cursor\n  autocmd BufReadPre * autocmd FileType <buffer> ++once\n    \\ if !&diff && &ft !~# 'commit\\|rebase' && line(\"'\\\"\") > 1 && line(\"'\\\"\") <= line(\"$\") | exe 'normal! g`\"' | endif\n```\nAgain, it won't jump to the line I was at when closing the file. However, it works perfectly fine when testing on files like ```testfile.txt```. Only ```testfile.c``` and ```testfile.md``` cause trouble. So maybe the problem lies somewhere else (filetype-detection) than shada... ",
